WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.000
[Amit Varma]: India is a democracy of course and the state is supposed to be subservient to the wishes of the people.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And that makes it imperative that all of us common citizens pay more attention to economics.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Economics matters, public policy matters.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:50.000
[Amit Varma]: They affect our lives in a million ways that go unseen.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
[Unknown]: Our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:15.000
[Amit Varma]: In the last few episodes I've taken deep dives into history and philosophy, discussing books by the likes of Ram Guha, Tyler Carvin, Stephen Pinker, Gyan Prakash, Matt Ridley and Manu Pillay.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
[Amit Varma]: I even had an episode on cricket with Harsha Bhogle.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.000
[Amit Varma]: But no matter where I go, I'll always come back to economics because hey, it's bloody important.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Starting today, I'm going to have an episode every few weeks that is an economics ramble.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:39.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll just ask a couple of economist friends to drop in and we'll chat about the economic landscape around us and try to illuminate more unseen effects of the policies of our overlords.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:45.000
[Amit Varma]: My guests today are both good friends of mine who have appeared on the show and I hope they'll remain regular guests as time goes by.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.000
[Amit Varma]: Vivek Kaur is India's most prolific economics journalist.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:55.000
[Amit Varma]: He writes an average of 33.2 pieces every week for various publications in India.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:01.000
[Amit Varma]: He's also written four books, the Easy Money Trilogy and India's Big Government. You can buy them all on Amazon.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:09.000
[Amit Varma]: My second guest today is my good friend Kumar Anand with whom I have had more cups of coffee than any other person alive.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
[Amit Varma]: So when I die of liver failure, you know who to blame.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Kumar is an economist who currently works with Naidisha and he also put together the Indian Liberals Project.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Before I begin my conversation with Vivek and Kumar though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Like me, are you someone who loves fine art but can't really afford to have paintings by the artists you like hanging on your walls?

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, worry no more. Head on over to IndianColors.com.

