[Amit Varma]: They accept bulk orders for corporate and festival gifting but even if you want to buy just for yourself or a friend, head on over to IndianColors.com.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:30.000
[Amit Varma]: That's colors with an OU and if you want a 20% discount, apply the code IVM20. That's IVM for IVM podcast.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
[Amit Varma]: IVM20 for a 20% discount at IndianColors.com.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Kumar and Vivek, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
[Guest 1]: Thank you, man.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:48.000
[Amit Varma]: So, Vivek, you kind of got here a little late because you were stuck in Bombay traffic and for that reason you haven't heard what I said about you in the introduction.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:55.000
[Amit Varma]: You'll hear that when the episode comes out and for that reason also we won't have a particularly long episode today, maybe an hour or so.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And we won't go into some of the reader questions that we asked people to submit on Twitter.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Those are for next time. This is going to be a regular feature. Hopefully, you guys will kind of keep returning but that's enough of me rambling and let's get to the economics ramble part of it.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Vivek, we are recording this on Feb 7th and the union budget was just out last week.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.000
[Amit Varma]: What were your views on it? I know you've written some 83 pieces on it already.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
[Amit Varma]: No, I just wrote around 8.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Just 8? Are you serious?

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:31.000
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I wrote 8. But that's not, I mean I had written 11 a couple of years back. This year I didn't write as many.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
[Guest 2]: So, before we get to that, do you repeat yourself in these 8 pieces or do you find different pieces to sell?

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:51.000
[Guest 2]: Of course, it can't be. So, in an interim budget it would be difficult to write 8 new pieces but in a fresh, in a normal budget, 10-11 pieces is pretty okay. There's nothing great about it. You can easily write 10-11 new pieces.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:06:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So, before we go back to the question, just to sort of digress, all the listeners obviously know that Vivek Kaul is the most prolific writer out there and you're writing some 50 pieces a week or whatever it is.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:05.000
[Amit Varma]: What's your work ethic like? How do you manage to write so many pieces?

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:17.000
[Guest 2]: No, so see what happens is, I don't write 50 pieces a week. So, in a good week I write around probably 10-11 pieces. In a bad week I write around 5-6.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:23.000
[Guest 2]: Kumar and I are suppressing our laughter. Like 10 pieces is nothing.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:25.000
[Guest 2]: Also because of what you said in the intro.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:41.000
[Guest 2]: So, basically see, what happens is in many pieces, like I wrote 3 pieces for Equity Master this week on the budget and they were all, so basically I wrote one piece on how the fiscal deficit should not be taken seriously.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:07:01.000
[Guest 2]: Then I wrote another piece, while writing that piece, the second idea on how FCI, Food Corporation of India is used to sort of manipulate fiscal deficit numbers. And then I wrote another piece on how FCI is used during election years to sort of benefit the political party which is in power.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:15.000
[Guest 2]: So, if you look at the core idea at the heart of these 3 pieces, it was basically the same. But given that, if I had figured everything out at the very beginning of writing the first piece, I would have written only one piece.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:21.000
[Guest 2]: But what happened was, when writing the first piece, I figured out the second one and when I wrote the second one, I figured out the third one.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.000
[Amit Varma]: So, it's like a Chinese box of rabbit holes.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:35.000
[Guest 2]: So, you keep saying, the economy, when you write on the economy, there are so many things that one thing leads to another. And if you are curious enough, I don't think writing 6-7 pieces is a big deal.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:41.000
[Guest 2]: Because ultimately it takes around what, 2 hours to write a 1000 word piece, not more than that.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:53.000
[Guest 2]: So, on that, and given that a lot of it is basically you are building on something that you have already written. So, you are essentially, it's all there in your head, you are just rewriting.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:04.000
[Guest 2]: Like if you were to ask me to write on the fiscal deficit, so 300, the basic 300 words on what is fiscal deficit, why is it important, I mean all that is already there.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:14.000
[Guest 2]: So, you are not like reinventing the wheel in the strictest sense of the term. So, basically most columns that one writes are not written from scratch.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:20.000
[Amit Varma]: So, let's shift attention from yourself to the budget.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:41.000
[Guest 2]: I just thought, it was an out and out election budget, I mean like interim budgets tend to be. And what was disappointing was the fact that some good schemes were launched without any preparation.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:56.000
[Guest 2]: So, take the biggest thing in the budget which was PM Kisan, essentially an income support scheme for farmers, small and marginal farmers with land holding of around 2 hectares, which is nearly 5 acres.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:18.000
[Guest 2]: So, now the basic problem here is that the government wants to give them 6000 rupees per year, 2000 rupees in 3 installments, and in order to ensure that they do it before elections, the scheme has essentially been initiated with a retrospective effect from December 1st.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:27.000
[Guest 2]: So, basically by March 31st, before March 31st, the first installment of 2000 rupees should have reached these farmers.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:38.000
[Guest 2]: Now the problem is how will you identify these farmers, I mean who are these farmers who have, you know, 2 hectares or less or households, farming households basically.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest 2]: Now, for that you need digital land records, which are not available through the length and breadth of the country, you know, a state like Karnataka has land records, but a state like Bihar which actually needs this support, you know, there is nothing there.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:16.000
[Guest 2]: So, or even Uttar Pradesh, so you know, these are the states which actually need, you know, need the support. The second thing is a lot of people have pointed out is that many of these people who own this land are no longer farmers, you know, I mean, they're probably living in cities and it's someone else who's farming on their behalf.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:26.000
[Guest 2]: So, what happens to them? Then there is the other, there is a pension scheme, which has been launched for people in the informal sector.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Again, a bit of…

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:35.000
[Amit Varma]: But if you go back to the hand out to farmers, I mean, which comes to really 500 bucks a month for each of them over a year, which isn't much at all.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:44.000
[Amit Varma]: So, even assuming implementation could be perfect, you could identify all the farmers and actually give them that money, do you really think it would make much of a difference?

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:54.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, see, it will not make, it will make some difference, you know, for, so, you know, again, to sort of, if you look at the income inequality that prevails through the length and breadth of India.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:04.000
[Guest 2]: Now, in a state like Bihar, which has a per capita income of around 38,000, a 6000 rupee payment per month will definitely make a lot of difference.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest 2]: You're saying it will make a difference in Bihar, maybe not in Kerala.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:15.000
[Guest 2]: But Kerala also has a lot of, you know, marginal farmers, because if you look at plot sizes in Kerala, agriculture plot sizes, they're very, very small.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
[Guest 2]: In fact, they're smaller than that, those in Bihar.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:22.000
[Guest 2]: So, Bihar, I think the average plot size is around 0.5, 0.5 hectares.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
[Guest 2]: In Kerala, it's around 0.3, 0.33, something like that.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And just off the top of your head, then what would you say are the chances that something like this can be implemented?

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
[Guest 2]: So, all these poor farmers in Bihar actually get the money.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
[Guest 2]: See, that's the irony of the whole situation.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:43.000
[Guest 2]: States which have better land records actually do not need these schemes as much as states which do not have land records.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:51.000
[Guest 2]: So, in an ideal world, this should have been done in July 2014, when the first budget was presented.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:59.000
[Guest 2]: And the next two years, or whatever time it would have taken, should have been spent in building these records, in building these databases.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:05.000
[Guest 2]: Like the government went around, you know, building the Aadhaar database or opening Jan Dhan accounts.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:09.000
[Guest 2]: This should also have been done on a similar war footing.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:14.000
[Guest 2]: Then, you know, it would have made, it would have made some difference.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Except now when they're desperate for votes.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. And I don't see how it's going to be implemented in a period of less than two months.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Kumar, what are your sort of views on handouts?

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:29.000
[Guest 1]: So, going back to the question you, the secondary question that you had asked related to the income support,

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.000
[Guest 1]: which is, will 500 rupees per month on the average will make a difference?

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:40.000
[Guest 1]: I think it will make a big difference, a huge difference, because the money in your pocket that you receive from the government or when you earn,

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
[Guest 1]: always makes a difference to you on the margin.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:51.000
[Guest 1]: So, for someone who does not have anything, 500 or 2000 rupees on the margin is, it could be a big, big amount.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:57.000
[Guest 1]: You know, imagine if you don't have anything, those first 100 rupees is what will get you your lunch or breakfast, you know, not on the margin.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:05.000
[Guest 2]: So, can I just interrupt? So, again, just to take his point forward, now, Bihar, the per capita income is 38,000, 39,000.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
[Guest 2]: So, per capita is essentially the mean that we are talking about.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
[Guest 2]: The median income would be even lower.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:16.000
[Guest 2]: So, the income of an average Bihari would be much lower than the per capita income in the state. Right.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:23.000
[Guest 2]: So, let's say someone who's making 20,000 rupees a year or 15,000 rupees a year, I mean, 6,000 rupees is a huge, huge amount of difference.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:29.000
[Guest 2]: So, it just depends on which part of, and there are large parts of India where this is needed.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:33.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, and what government is estimating, I think is about 12 crore families it will cover.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:38.000
[Guest 1]: So, which is about half of the households, entire households, that about 25 crore families in the country.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
[Guest 1]: So, 50% of the households will get covered.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:48.000
[Guest 1]: So, to me, it looks like a big scheme. Well, implement, whether it will get implemented, whether everyone will receive the money is a different question altogether.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
[Amit Varma]: So, I'm not very hopeful about that.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:59.000
[Amit Varma]: So, before we go back to the budget, this is actually a good time to sort of take a diversion for a moment and talk about the Congress's promise of the minimum guaranteed income for the poor.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Because that again appears to be a similar way of not actually caring about fixing structural problems.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.000
[Amit Varma]: But here's a handout and we'll bribe you and get your votes and whatever.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And Kumar, I know you wrote a very long essay recently for a French publication on the UBI.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And this of course is not the UBI. But can you share some of your insights from that and therefore what you think about this?

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:29.000
[Guest 1]: So, I think people who are policy wonks have started describing these programs as QUBI, quasi universal basic income.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:35.000
[Guest 1]: So, both Congress's proposal a week before the budget came out, and now the BJP's proposal.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:47.000
[Guest 1]: Congress's proposal, I would say on the margin is worse than BJP's proposal because what they are saying is that they will identify a poverty line and anyone falling short of that, they will provide the bridge.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:56.000
[Guest 1]: So, suppose if I have said that one lakh rupees per annum income is the one where everyone should get, if you are falling short by 50,000, I'll give you 50,000.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
[Guest 1]: If you're falling short by 80,000, I'll give you 80,000.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:05.000
[Guest 1]: Now, what that means, the guy who is deciding how much money you are falling short of. Tremendous discretion.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:13.000
[Guest 1]: So, in fact, the next job that I will be looking for is that if I can be the person who decides how much you are making and you know, therefore the bridge.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean the system can be so hard.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:20.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so, of course, and in all of this, the big challenge is the fiscal constraint.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:29.000
[Guest 1]: So, once you start on this road, a country which is developed with a per capita income of 40-50,000 US dollars can think about doing it.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:42.000
[Guest 1]: As part of the research when I was doing on UBI, I learned that Hillary Clinton very seriously considered running on the platform of UBI and abandoned it because the numbers didn't add up.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
[Guest 1]: They certainly don't add up for India.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:49.000
[Guest 1]: And once you start, every budget you will see more and more, you know, promises in terms of numbers.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:54.000
[Amit Varma]: My largest sort of philosophical question is, there's always going to be a trade-off between growth and redistribution.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Do you grow the pie or do you redistribute parts of it?

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And that is a trade-off which when a poor country like India whose first imperative is to remove poverty, I'm not sure if that's sort of a trade-off we can afford to make on the side of redistribution.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Amit Varma]: We need to grow wealth first.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:11.000
[Guest 1]: Exactly.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:24.000
[Amit Varma]: So, what are your sort of feelings on the broad, this philosophical outlook that we will do handouts and we will bribe voters the best we can to get their votes and ultimately nothing really changes the poor remain poor.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:25.000
[Guest 1]: Exactly.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:31.000
[Guest 1]: So, this brings me back to the budget speech which I was reading and I have read it carefully, each of the sentences.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:45.000
[Guest 1]: One thing that stood out for me more than the income support for the farmers or the pension scheme for the unorganized sector laborers is 143 crore LED bulbs were distributed by the government, subsidized or in some form or the other.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.000
[Guest 1]: That means 1.1 bulb for 130 crore Indians.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.000
[Guest 1]: I never received that bulb.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:54.000
[Guest 2]: No, but that hardly means anything.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
[Amit Varma]: But these bulbs were available if you wanted to.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.000
[Guest 1]: It's not a point of the amount of money.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
[Guest 1]: It's also a point of your mindset.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:08.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, that's the point I'm trying to make is that and once you start, it just you know, kind of a bulb sort of went in my own head and you started reading some of the other paragraphs.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
[Unknown]: So, you did get a free bulb from them.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, in some ways.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:26.000
[Guest 1]: So, once you start reading all the other sentences, you realize that how a lot more attention has been given to the provision of private goods, which you would assume that people who take care on their own will provide, you know, work for it or you know, whatever and provide for themselves.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:31.000
[Guest 1]: And the things that the government should be doing, you know, our public goods, national defense, law and order, etc.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.000
[Guest 1]: You know, making sure that contacts are enforced, etc.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
[Guest 1]: Those are the job of the government and they will do it.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:40.000
[Guest 1]: Budget is entirely looks to me is focused on provision of private goods.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:44.000
[Guest 1]: Some of the things that are LED bulbs, of course, 6 crore LPG cylinders.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:55.000
[Guest 1]: You'd assume that is a classic case of a private good building houses, building toilets as part of such a Bharat mission, which you would assume that if you really want to take care of sanitation and cleanliness.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:06.000
[Guest 1]: The way to fix it would be rather look at the root cause of it, whether it's property rights or devolution of power to the local governments, but rather than running a national mission on it, electricity connection and of course, food grain, etc.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:07.000
[Guest 1]: So, look at it.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:14.000
[Guest 1]: It looks like you are engaged more and more increasing every year in the provision of private goods.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:20.000
[Guest 1]: The budget looks like to me that and which brings to your point, which is again the classic case of redistribution, you know.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Guest 1]: So, almost all of this is financed by taxes one way or the other, whether it's inflation tax, deficit financing or through, you know, just tax revenues, which are collected.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I wrote a piece about this in the Times of India this Sunday.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:40.000
[Amit Varma]: So, where I repeated a limerick I once wrote for the Times of India, which I'll repeat here, which is the limericks called politics and this is how it goes.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:44.000
[Amit Varma]: A neta who loves currency notes told me what his line of work denotes.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
[Amit Varma]: It is kind of funny.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
[Amit Varma]: We steal people's money and use some of it to buy their votes.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop code and and my contention in that column was that in India, all good politics will ultimately be bad economics because that is what sells and gets you votes.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Do you agree with that Vivek?

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:01.000
[Guest 1]: Why specific to India?

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.000
[Guest 1]: So, would you say that is true for all countries on this particular to India?

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
[Amit Varma]: That's a good question.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Guest 1]: What do you think?

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:13.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, the nature of I think we wrote a piece on politics is equal to bribery sometime ago, looking through public choice lines.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:17.000
[Guest 1]: I think that would be true for all countries and not all democracies.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:29.000
[Amit Varma]: It is rational for voters to remain ignorant about economics and therefore they will and and and voters tend to think in zero some ways and therefore, you know, handouts are attractive to them and they're not really short term.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:33.000
[Guest 1]: The scene unseen is far away and you Vivek is twitching.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:38.000
[Guest 2]: No, no, what basically, you know, I don't complicate things as much as Anand did.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:51.000
[Guest 2]: My take is very simple. See, basically, Narendra Modi, the way I look at him, you know, he is essentially a narrative builder.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:52.000
[Guest 2]: Sure.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:55.000
[Guest 2]: People call him a nation builder, but he's basically a narrative builder.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:01.000
[Guest 2]: And he has been losing track of the narrative for the last four, five months.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:10.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, there is no denying that. I mean, you may one may not like Rahul Gandhi, but he's come back forcefully over the last few months.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:25.000
[Guest 2]: So this speech by Piyush Goyal and to his credit, he did a much better job than Arun Jaitley possibly would have was essentially a attempt to get control of the narrative again.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:34.000
[Guest 2]: And which is why he sort of went back, you know, went to, you know, if you look at the speech, it's essentially a summary of what Modi has supposedly done.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
[Guest 2]: How he projects himself.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:41.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's just that there's nothing more to it. You know, he's talked about all, you know, all the talking points are there.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:59.000
[Guest 2]: Beyond that, it has talking points, which Modi can go and sell to the audience in the next three to four months, which not four months, but two to three months, which he will definitely be on the road and will be communicating with the people of the country directly.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:14.000
[Guest 2]: So it has given him these talking points, you know, you have the income scheme, then you have the pension scheme and everything else that he is supposedly done.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:29.000
[Guest 2]: So I think it was nothing more than, it is good politics. I mean, it was nothing more than, you know, a good pre-election speech, which the finance minister did a commendable job of, you know, executing.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:32.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, even look at, I'll give you a very simple example.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:40.000
[Guest 2]: Now, let's, you know, he talked about how the defense budget for the first time was crossing three lakh crore and everybody clapped.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:56.000
[Guest 2]: But then what was the defense budget up until now? You know, I mean, and if you look at the numbers, the increase is just, you know, a couple of percentage points, which is lesser than the prevailing rate of inflation, right?

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:03.000
[Guest 2]: Where is this money going to? A lot of this money in the so-called defense budget now goes towards salaries and pensions.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:08.000
[Guest 2]: It is not going towards, you know, what is, you know, actually…

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:15.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, most of our weapons, I forget the figure, but it's more than 90%. Most of the weapons the Indian army has are hopeless, outdated by decades.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:25.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, so if you look at how the entire speech was structured, it was essentially structured to catch attention of people.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:35.000
[Guest 2]: It was structured to help the media. You know, if you look at newspapers these days, they are, there are special editions designed for the budget.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:44.000
[Guest 2]: And if you look at those pages very carefully, there are boxes, which, you know, in which bullet points have to be filled.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:23:00.000
[Guest 2]: So, these, it was basically, you know, the speech was very, very bullet point driven so that, you know, the media could, you know, catch on to these bullet points easily and repeat it, you know, during the course of the day or the next morning.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:12.000
[Guest 2]: The other point is, you know, in an interim budget, you don't make, you know, big changes like this, you know, like the income support scheme, but the BJP did it.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:28.000
[Guest 2]: And in fact, I was on TV on the budget day and the BJP spokesperson, in fact, two BJP spokespersons at different points of time justified it by saying, but the Congress did this in 2014 and did this in 2009.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:38.000
[Guest 2]: And, you know, there is a line which I like to sort of repeat and it's a line from the movie Diwaar, which is like, auron ke paap ginane se apne paap kam nahi ho jata hai.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:41.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, two wrongs don't make a right.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
[Guest 2]: Bollywood's articulation of what about it.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:24:06.000
[Guest 2]: Yes, so, you know, two wrongs don't make a right, but essentially this was an out and out election speech, election budget designed to help Narendra Modi and the other BJP leaders to sort of get talking points, which they can pick up and go talk about at, you know, various points.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:13.000
[Guest 2]: In fact, if you watch TV on the budget day, you'd realize that all BJP spokesperson were basically saying the same thing.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
[Guest 2]: They were not answering the questions.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:20.000
[Guest 2]: They had these three, four points, which they were just going and building the narrative.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:26.000
[Guest 2]: Yes, so it was essentially nothing more, you know, just another exercise in narrative building.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:40.000
[Guest 2]: Also to sort of, you know, the limerick you sort of talked about, you know, politics, there is a very nice line, there was a Shahrukh Khan movie many years back called Oh Darling Yeh Hai India.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:43.000
[Guest 2]: So there is a very nice song in that movie.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:50.000
[Guest 2]: And I don't remember the song, but there's a nice line in that song, which goes jo bacha nahi wo baat diya.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:59.000
[Guest 2]: You know, Oh Darling Yeh Hai India, so what we haven't even saved, we have already distributed or at least planned to.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:03.000
[Guest 2]: So, yeah, there's another point I wanted to make.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:10.000
[Guest 2]: So, the Congress, you know, minimum income guarantee scheme, Big 19, you know, which makes 10 billion.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Is that your term?

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:17.000
[Guest 2]: I don't know, otherwise someone else would have also, but I use it in a piece in the Mint.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:22.000
[Amit Varma]: So it is your term, like Pakora Nomics too, listeners of my show know this Pakora Nomics is your term.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:36.000
[Guest 2]: So, Big 19, I think, you know, I look at it in a slightly different way, in the sense that, and I'm not just talking about the Congress's scheme, but the entire scheme, any income support scheme.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:51.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, I think it's, I mean, I wouldn't have said this a few years back, but now I think having looked at, you know, enough data and enough Indian economies, I think it's necessary because you have parts of India, which will never catch up with other parts of India.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:26:00.000
[Guest 2]: You know, if you know, if Bihar grows at 11%, I mean, it will, if Karnataka stops growing today, Bihar will probably get there in another 15 years.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:14.000
[Guest 2]: So it is not fair, you know, whatever, if you know, India is a nation, you know, attempts have to be made to help parts of the country, which are not growing at an adequate speed and which have been left back.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:22.000
[Amit Varma]: I think the larger point there is that you are right that in states like Bihar and all people are in poverty, it's our moral imperative to get them out of that.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's completely right.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:27.000
[Amit Varma]: But whether they catch up with Karnataka or not is not an issue.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:31.000
[Amit Varma]: No, but my point is, it's the divide is just way too big.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:36.000
[Amit Varma]: I wouldn't look at the divide. I would just look at the absolute numbers and you're right, the absolute numbers are abysmal.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:41.000
[Amit Varma]: But to talk about it in terms of the divide is completely pointless. That's a wrong metric.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:46.000
[Amit Varma]: I'd rather talk about poverty than inequality because the two are very different and India's problem is poverty.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, at one level, yes.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:57.000
[Guest 2]: So, no, so what the point I was making was that now obviously, you know, you need a lot of money to do it.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:09.000
[Guest 2]: Now, the Congress minimum income guarantee scheme, even though very, you know, the details available are very sketchy, but from the way they've been talking, it would definitely cost more than 75,000 crores.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:20.000
[Guest 2]: Obviously, there are problems with this scheme as to how do you identify, you know, let's say the cutoff is 50,000 points. How do you figure out, you know, the person eligible is making that kind of money,

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:26.000
[Guest 2]: especially in the informal sector where payments are in cash and also payments tend to vary.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:30.000
[Guest 2]: It's not like you get the same amount of money every day or every week.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:32.000
[Guest 2]: So how do you figure all that out?

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:39.000
[Guest 2]: You know, it's easy if all the money is coming into a bank account and then you can, you know, do some 180 day average or something like that.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:28:00.000
[Guest 2]: But having said that, you know, I think it's also one if the country were to look at a bigger income support scheme, I think it's sort of makes sense because, and you know, we obviously have to fund it properly because that bill there would run into lakhs of, you know, it would easily run into 9, 10, 11 lakh crore.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:03.000
[Guest 2]: So how do you fund something like that?

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:18.000
[Guest 2]: And if, you know, in order to fund something like that, the only way is to, for the government is to sell all the assets that it has been sitting on what Mr. Anand's current employer, Mr. Jain's been talking for a while.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:28.000
[Guest 2]: So I think it's a reasonably good idea, but obviously it will not happen because no politician worth his salt will do anything like that.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:42.000
[Guest 2]: So if someone were to do it and do it properly, it would be an excellent way of curtailing, you know, India's big government, which is in places which it shouldn't be.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:50.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, the government should basically be concentrating on five, six basic things, defense, external affairs, railways, roads.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:55.000
[Amit Varma]: As you keep saying, a strong and limited government instead of a weak but vastly spread out.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:29:00.000
[Guest 2]: Yes, all over the place, but this is again a utopia. It's a utopian dream. It's not going to happen.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:11.000
[Guest 2]: And what will essentially happen is we'll have all these half-baked income support schemes, which will operate on top of all the schemes that we already have.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:14.000
[Guest 2]: Now, you know, this is a point I made in my Mint article.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:21.000
[Guest 2]: So basically what, you know, Praveen Chakravartty has been saying is that, you know, they'll be rational about the entire thing.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:29.000
[Guest 2]: So obviously it means that, you know, they'll look at new ways of raising taxes and they'll also look at ways of cutting down on current expenditure.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:34.000
[Guest 2]: Now, if you look at current expenditure, you will have to cut down on things like food subsidies.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:42.000
[Guest 2]: Now, it's easy to talk about cutting down food subsidies, but the moment you start getting into it, there are too many problems that crop up.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:47.000
[Guest 2]: Now, the first thing that will happen is that, you know, how is food subsidy offered?

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:56.000
[Guest 2]: It is offered through Food Corporation of India, which buys rice and wheat directly from farmers at a minimum support price, which the government announces.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:07.000
[Guest 2]: This is then distributed through the public distribution system at a very low price to meet the needs of the National Food Security Act and other, you know, welfare measures of the government.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:14.000
[Guest 2]: The government then compensates the Food Corporation of India for this subsidy that it offers.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:20.000
[Guest 2]: And now, if the food subsidy were to be cut down, then, you know, by its very definition,

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:26.000
[Guest 2]: FCA would also have to cut down on procuring, you know, rice and wheat that it does.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:32.000
[Guest 2]: If it procures less, then what happens to all the, you know, infrastructure that it has built?

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:37.000
[Guest 2]: What happens to the public distribution system that is in place?

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:41.000
[Unknown]: These are not easy, you know, there are too many entrenched…

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:46.000
[Guest 2]: And there are states where the public distribution system actually works pretty well.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
[Guest 2]: What about those states?

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:53.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, so why, you know, I mean, there will definitely be protests.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:31:05.000
[Guest 2]: Also, you know, I think the two pilots which have happened for distributing cash instead of food happened in Pondicherry and Chandigarh.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:20.000
[Guest 2]: And I don't think they have, you know, received, they've been very successful because the system that is, you know, is currently there is so well entrenched that they basically managed to pull down the experiments.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
[Amit Varma]: So, Kumar, let me cut to you here.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Since our friend brought you into the conversation himself.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:26.000
[Guest 1]: Thanks for the plug, Vivek.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so you work for Naidisha, which is started by Rajesh Jain.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:35.000
[Unknown]: We did an episode with Rajesh a long time back where he explained his Dhanwapsi idea.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:44.000
[Amit Varma]: Now the thing what I have always thought about such handouts is that they are and ultimately the UBI is at a vast level just extremely unfeasible.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:51.000
[Amit Varma]: The numbers don't work and there are ethical issues with them as well for the large scale coercion that they involve.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:32:08.000
[Amit Varma]: But your point, what you guys say in Dhanwapsi is that this you don't need to redistribute to have a UBI that you can have a UBI feasibly if you just look at all the unused property that the government sits on, which is technically the property of the people.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And it has no business being lying idle when it's not being used by the state.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:19.000
[Amit Varma]: So the state should sell it and use that money for the welfare of the people to whom it belongs.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.000
[Guest 1]: Tell me a little bit more about that briefly.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:24.000
[Guest 1]: The point is here is I'll go a little bit back in the history.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:29.000
[Guest 1]: So since independence, we pursued the central planning model and the five-year plan.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:39.000
[Guest 1]: And what we did that to do the Soviet model planning, the big difference between Soviet Union and India, of course, is that India was a democracy while Soviet Union was not.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:43.000
[Guest 1]: We had private property as a fundamental right, property rights are fundamental right, but they did not.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:46.000
[Guest 1]: Every resource there belonged to the state.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:51.000
[Guest 1]: So to pursue planning, the only way you could do those planning if resources are available to you.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:56.000
[Guest 1]: So over a period of time, this Indian state has continued to accumulate more and more resources.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:03.000
[Guest 1]: So you'll remember the recent piece that I did for Pragati with my colleague Reshu, which is about how the number of CPSCs has grown over the years.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:10.000
[Guest 1]: In 50-51, it was 5. In 2013-14, when the current government came to power, it was 290.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:19.000
[Guest 1]: And as of 31st March 2018, the number stood at 339. So they have added more than about one CPSC every month that they have in power.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:26.000
[Guest 1]: So the state has continued to amass more and more resources in case of CPSCs, land, minerals, etc.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:31.000
[Guest 1]: So you nationalized all that. 70% of the banking business is not accounted for here.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:40.000
[Guest 1]: So if you take all that into account, then the ballpark figure that we have is that at the rate of 1 lakh rupees per Indian household,

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:45.000
[Guest 1]: you'll be able to finance the return of this wealth. Remember, I'm calling it return of wealth.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:53.000
[Guest 1]: It's called the term NVAPSI and not a universal basic income, which is financed out of taxes or some sort of redistribution.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:34:06.000
[Guest 1]: It is redistribution, but taking away from the state itself, which over many, many years has continued to amass and currently which is lying either unused and what's still misused or abused.

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:15.000
[Guest 1]: So you monetize it, put them into a fund, which is different from consolidated funds of India and use that fund only for the purpose of returning it back to people.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:22.000
[Guest 1]: No other purpose. So it's not used for government's current consumption purposes, but money directly hands.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:28.000
[Guest 1]: So I call it the right way of doing UBI. Just to get into the conversation on UBI, because people are talking about it.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:33.000
[Guest 1]: And as we discussed earlier that how India absolutely does not have the fiscal bandwidth.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:37.000
[Guest 1]: This is one way that you can do it. So all the resources which are lying idle.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:42.000
[Guest 1]: But as Vivek rightly said, you know, politically, it looks quite improbable.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:51.000
[Guest 1]: But at the same time, if enough people talk about it, and if people start looking at it and demanding it, then I don't think it will be, you know, an impossible thing anymore.

