00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.000
[Amit Varma]: But both of you actually named the book.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:10.000
[Guest 2]: So I would like to add, I think the Indian politicians and economics should also read this book called India Unbound by Gurcharan Das.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:11.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.000
[Guest 1]: I also had a book in mind.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:18.000
[Guest 1]: So Indian policymakers should read De Soto's Mystery of Capital.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:19.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:25.000
[Guest 1]: Understand the importance of informal economy and how important the property rights are, which our good friend.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Capitalism doesn't work.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:30.000
[Amit Varma]: So I read that book, which is which is where I got the phrase debt capital from.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:36.000
[Amit Varma]: And since then, I just, you know, it's like in that Manoj Nath Chamlin film, the Bruce Willis says, I see dead people everywhere.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.000
[Amit Varma]: I look around and I see dead capital everywhere.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.000
[Guest 1]: De Soto would be very happy with me.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.000
[Amit Varma]: All the unused and misused lying assets.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:44.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Now you're pushing your agenda.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop it.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:50.000
[Amit Varma]: The next question, Vivek, you go first for this one.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:55.000
[Amit Varma]: What is the one bad idea that all our policymakers share?

00:38:55.000 --> 00:39:09.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, I guess you would probably say that one bad idea at the central government level is to keep launching new schemes because, you know, the Indian bureaucracy is like a funnel where it's very wide at the top.

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:15.000
[Guest 2]: And when it comes to designing, planning, talking about a new scheme, they're pretty good about it.

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
[Guest 2]: Like, I mean, look at PM Kisan.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:18.000
[Guest 2]: Sounds very good.

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:23.000
[Guest 2]: But the moment you need to execute it, the lower bureaucracy is already very, very burdened.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:32.000
[Guest 2]: So like, you know, in the 2016-17 economic survey, Arvind Subramaniam had said that there are 950 centrally sponsored schemes.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:37.000
[Guest 2]: So how is anyone supposed to keep track of that?

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:42.000
[Guest 2]: So launching one more scheme on top of that is remarkably stupid.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:46.000
[Guest 2]: So take the, you know, the pension scheme that's been launched for the informal sector.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:49.000
[Guest 2]: Now, it's not like India doesn't have pension schemes.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:54.000
[Guest 2]: You know, there are enough, there is public provident fund has been around since the late 60s.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:57.000
[Guest 2]: And it is available to anyone and everyone.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:11.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, you could have easily played around, you know, had an option in within that scheme, where the same scheme could have been implemented without, you know, going, you know, starting one more new scheme.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:15.000
[Guest 2]: But then, you know, it wouldn't have, you couldn't, you know, build a narrative.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:20.000
[Guest 2]: You know, in order to build a narrative, you always need something new.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:25.000
[Guest 1]: My answer is a bit similar to Vivek's.

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:35.000
[Guest 1]: Again, when I was reading the budget speech, felt if the common narrative there is the government, in this case, the central government is thinking only they can do things.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:42.000
[Guest 1]: So the number of new schemes, which have the title Pradhan Mantri, you know, and the way it starts, you know, Pradhan Mantri this Yojana, Pradhan Mantri that Yojana.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:46.000
[Guest 1]: So the My Bab Sarkar, the notion, the centralization.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:55.000
[Guest 1]: So for me, that one bad idea, which all policymakers want is centralization, no matter what government there is, they all pursue amassing greater and greater power at the center.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:59.000
[Guest 1]: The reason I say this is there's a lot of merit in decentralization.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:07.000
[Guest 1]: Of course, you devolve power to the local government, but somehow that agenda, the narrative is not there at all from politicians.

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:12.000
[Guest 1]: If there are local politicians, no one is saying that why not devolve power to the local governments.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:16.000
[Guest 1]: We did those 73rd and 74th amendment way back in 1992.

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:20.000
[Guest 1]: It has been more than 25 years, but they have not been implemented at least in the spirit.

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:26.000
[Guest 1]: So I would say it is the continued centralization of power in the hands of central government.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:31.000
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you and to add to that, I'll answer the question by saying that it's not just a centralization.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:38.000
[Amit Varma]: Instead, the basic mindset that the state is a solution to the state is or holds a solution to all problems.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:47.000
[Amit Varma]: That status mindset, I think everything that India has achieved has been achieved by Indian society and the Indians and despite the Indian state.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:52.000
[Amit Varma]: And every time the state gets a little bit out of the way, we do better like it did in 91.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:42:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think this is fundamentally something that we don't understand because we don't understand spontaneous order and how societies organize themselves to fulfill their own needs through markets, for example.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:09.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is in fact, the biggest cause of our agricultural crisis.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:21.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, something that, you know, we've both written on many times that, you know, the liberalization of 91 did not touch agriculture and agriculture is paternalized and it's kept in the cycle of dependency.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's why we have this sort of massive.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:28.000
[Guest 1]: Any decision making should happen closest to the people rather than further away.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. Now, my next question is a related question, which should be not so easy for both of you guys.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:37.000
[Amit Varma]: What is the one good idea that all our policy makers share?

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's go with Kumar.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:45.000
[Guest 1]: I think as far as the rhetoric is concerned, so that may not be the case in actual policies or implementation.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:53.000
[Guest 1]: But almost every politician in the country, while presenting the budget or in, you know, appearing on television, a speech, etc.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:55.000
[Guest 1]: Do not ask for more taxes.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:58.000
[Guest 1]: So they do not ask for increasing of duties.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:04.000
[Guest 1]: And they talk about ease of doing business with at least some kind of reverence, you know, though they may not be the best solution.

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:10.000
[Guest 1]: But the thing that how that low taxes is good, lesser regulations is good.

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:20.000
[Guest 1]: What happens in reality is a completely different matter, but at least, you know, no one is publicly opposing a low taxes, lower duties or ease of doing business.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:22.000
[Amit Varma]: I would say that is.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:23.000
[Amit Varma]: I have two observations here.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:30.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I mean, one observation obviously is that some of the rhetoric has changed, but they don't follow out on the rhetoric.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And from this, what follows is that this kind of rhetoric, the minimum government, maximum governance kind of rhetoric is rhetoric that is appealing to a small section of the elites.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Who also happen to be in media and so on and is for them only.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:50.000
[Amit Varma]: But they don't actually need to deliver on this because their constituency, which counts are the actual voting masses and they don't really care about it.

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:53.000
[Amit Varma]: That's that's sort of one cynical reaction to what you're saying.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:54.000
[Guest 1]: So reality is different.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:54.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:54.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:44:02.000
[Amit Varma]: The other non cynical reaction would be that yes, over time, what we have seen is a shifting of what is called what economists call the Overton window.

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:13.000
[Amit Varma]: The Overton window essentially is a definition of essentially indicates the window of acceptable discourse on a linear scale, which is normally organized around freedom.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And what happens is that over time that window shifts and things that were not acceptable 20 years ago may suddenly become acceptable today.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:37.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, at a social level, I've seen the Overton window shift in my own lifetime, where if 377 had been abolished in the 1980s, it would not have got the kind of response it has today, where today the response largely is that yes, it needed to be abolished.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course, there are widespread celebrations and all that.

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:43.000
[Amit Varma]: There may be that selection bias in play because I follow those circles.

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:55.000
[Amit Varma]: But regardless of that, I think in the 1980s, it would not have been like that at all. And a lot of people just wouldn't have gotten it and a lot of conservatives would have been more outspoken in the opposition of outlawing 377.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:45:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, in an economic sense, I think there was a time where, you know, high taxes were considered good and nobody would be talking about low taxation and blah, blah, blah.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think I agree with you that it's a positive sign that they're talking about it. But my sense is they're talking about it for, you know, optical reasons for one small part of the intelligence here.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And they don't really care about it at all. But I hope I'm wrong. And I hope the Overton window keeps shifting because rhetoric does matter, Vivek.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:38.000
[Guest 2]: I think, you know, one good thing that one could possibly say, you know, is the fact that, you know, once income taxes have sort of come down to a low level, they haven't really gone up again.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:43.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, even though, you know, there is too much fiddling around and, you know, we could do much better on our taxes front.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:54.000
[Guest 2]: But largely our tax rates have stayed more or less the same. So, yeah, we should say that we could possibly thank our politicians for that. So, right.

00:45:54.000 --> 00:46:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, my next question, two sort of broad general questions. And Kumar, you know, when I shared these on WhatsApp, you said that these are sort of related and you'd like to take them together.

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:12.000
[Amit Varma]: So, I'll just ask them together, which is that one, we are facing this massive jobs crisis, which is evident and which is why I also say that our jobs and agricultural crisis are so big that it doesn't really matter who wins the next round.

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:21.000
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't really matter who wins the next elections. We are screwed anyway. There's not much we can do about them, partly because none of the parties shows the mindset that you need to solve these particular problems.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:32.000
[Amit Varma]: But to stop rambling in this economics ramble episode, my quick question to you guys is one, what would you do to create jobs? And two, what would you do to fight poverty on a war footing?

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:42.000
[Guest 2]: Vivek is amused by my question. Why are you asking this? Nothing will happen. We know. What would you do?

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:51.000
[Guest 2]: This is like a prime time debate on TV, especially on the Hindi channels.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:47:03.000
[Guest 2]: So, what would you do if you were the Prime Minister of this country?

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:21.000
[Amit Varma]: So, basically, on what? So, when they ask this on TV, because I don't watch TV, it's… I mean, what will they say? Is it like zero-sum solutions? And is it like, you know, the standard T-shirt jokes?

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:33.000
[Guest 2]: No, so basically, you know, I think to answer your question seriously, the first thing… So, if you look at the interim budget, you know, the word jobs was used five times.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:46.000
[Guest 2]: And in very vague and in very vague contexts. So, the first thing to solve the jobs crisis is to acknowledge that it exists, which the current government refuses to do.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:58.000
[Guest 2]: What I find very, very funny is that, you know, when you tell them there is a crisis, they'll point out to, you know, data points like Uber and Ola have been recruiting, you know, drivers.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:10.000
[Guest 2]: But when you tell them that CMI survey shows that 1.1 crore Indians lost their jobs in 2018, then they'll come around and tell you, but that's private. Uber-Ola is also private.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:29.000
[Guest 2]: The, you know, the recent NSSO data, which the Business Standard published, I mean, the way they went around trying to deny that data was very, very disturbing, because, you know, a huge… NSSO is by far the largest survey that the government carries out.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:42.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, obviously, you know, the census would be much bigger, but census is not a survey. And a lot of things that the NSSO collects ultimately are, you know, go in as inputs into the GDP calculation.

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:57.000
[Guest 2]: So, if the NSSO data is also not kosher, then what is kosher? So, I mean, the broad point is that the first thing that the government needs to do in order to solve the jobs crisis is to acknowledge that it exists.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:01.000
[Guest 1]: That's the first thing. The second thing that…

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:04.000
[Guest 1]: So, Vivek will acknowledge that it exists, and then we'll come to the second thing.

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:05.000
[Guest 2]: No, he's come to the second thing.

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:11.000
[Guest 2]: No, no, the first thing is, yeah, that's the first thing. If you don't acknowledge, how will you solve it?

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:33.000
[Guest 2]: The second thing that has happened is, and, you know, a lot of people have talked about, see, basically, how, you know, if you look at the formula, if you look at the economic history, the one formula which stands out for countries which have gone from being developing countries to becoming developed countries is through exports of, you know, low end goods.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:44.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's happened to the US, UK, large parts of Europe, China, you name a country and that is how it is. That is something that is not happening in India.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:55.000
[Guest 2]: And very, very funnily, our engineering goods exports, which are highly skilled exports seem to be doing much better than, you know, exports which are labor intensive.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:50:20.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, given that there is a formula in place, so, you know, any government, I mean, the next government has to work towards ensuring that, you know, people who want to export, or even, you know, generally people who want to do business, transact, exchange things are allowed to do so.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:32.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this might sound like again, you know, one of those utopian answers, but I can object to the way you're using the word utopian because the utopia would refer to an end goal.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:36.000
[Amit Varma]: While this is, while I would see this as referring to a direction.

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:43.000
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I mean, what I mean by utopia here is that, you know, because this is never going to happen is what I mean.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:48.000
[Amit Varma]: It's never going to happen that we reach an ideal end state, but it can happen that we become better.

00:50:48.000 --> 00:51:01.000
[Guest 2]: So, if you look at many Indian states, and I mean, this is pretty well documented, we have, you know, there's an economist called Danny Roderick, and he uses a term called premature non-industrialization.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:08.000
[Guest 2]: And this was the term used in the economic survey a few years back by Arvind Subramaniam as well.

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:18.000
[Guest 2]: So, many Indian states have reached, you know, premature non-industrialization where the industry in the state has simply stopped growing.

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:24.000
[Guest 2]: So, the only Indian state which has ever crossed, where industry has crossed 20% of the state's GDP is Gujarat.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:39.000
[Guest 2]: Whereas a lot of other, you know, states, which you think are extremely industrialized states like Maharashtra and Tamil Nadu, achieved their high point in industry in the late 1980s.

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:52.000
[Guest 2]: A state like Uttar Pradesh has, you know, basically, the level of industry in that state is 10 to 12% of the GDP, and it has stopped industrializing.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:58.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, unless these states industrialize, I mean, there is no way they can go forward.

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:04.000
[Guest 2]: So, if you look at, you know, if you leave states, small states like Goa, which, you know, benefits…

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:12.000
[Amit Varma]: But what would you do to… like, this goes back to the classic thing that look, okay, economies grow, they start off in agriculture, then manufacturing, then services.

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course, in our case, you know, cheap labor was, you know, could have been a great strength, we could have been vegetarianized today, but our manufacturing revolution simply never happened because of the state.

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Because of labor laws and this license raj and all of that, it simply never happened.

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And instead, we had a bit of a services boom through the 90s and all of that.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:34.000
[Guest 2]: Thanks to… because the state did not understand what is happening.

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:36.000
[Unknown]: Which is why it was kind of…

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:43.000
[Amit Varma]: So, what do you do? Do you think that given the rise of automation across the world, there is still scope for a manufacturing revolution or we've missed the bus?

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:51.000
[Guest 2]: I think we've missed the bus, which is why, you know, I've sort of become a sort of… I mean, I have a soft corner for an income support scheme.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:54.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, I would have not had it five years back.

00:52:54.000 --> 00:53:04.000
[Guest 2]: But I think we've missed the bus clearly because, I mean, so, you know, people these days talk about the fact that China is sort of getting out of labor intensive manufacturing.

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:07.000
[Guest 2]: And, you know, there is a big opportunity.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:11.000
[Guest 2]: But, you know, countries like Vietnam and Bangladesh have caught on to it.

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:12.000
[Guest 2]: We haven't.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:18.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's surprising, you know, Bangladesh exports more textiles than India does.

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:27.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, so, yeah, so, I think we've missed, more or less missed the manufacturing and even the low-end export…

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Which brings me back to your point two.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Your point one is you'll acknowledge there's a jobs crisis.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Point two is what will you do?

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:38.000
[Guest 2]: So, see, the thing is, no, no, I mean, so, see, we're talking here, you know, this is like…

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:39.000
[Amit Varma]: This is a very good diagnosis.

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:40.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I obviously agree with you.

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:45.000
[Guest 2]: This is not binary, you know, what I'm trying to say is that, you know, once you acknowledge, you will do a few things.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:54.000
[Guest 2]: It may not work out to solve the problems through the length of breadth of, you know, India, but it will definitely benefit a few people somewhere, right?

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:57.000
[Guest 2]: So, these things are never binary, right?

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:06.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, so, I guess, first thing is you acknowledge and then you do all the things that have been done in the past to ensure that, you know…

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:12.000
[Amit Varma]: A lot of which the Modi government did promise in 2014 and absolutely did not deliver on, like reforming labor laws.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:15.000
[Guest 2]: And, you know, the thing that I find funny is that…

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:21.000
[Guest 2]: So, Martin Wolf has a piece in the Financial Times on how India will grow despite its politics.

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:24.000
[Guest 2]: And he's referred to some World Bank report that's come out.

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:27.000
[Guest 2]: I haven't read the report, but I've read the Martin Wolf piece.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:36.000
[Guest 2]: And, you know, the kind of things that he points out that these are the things that the Modi government has done, you know, stuff like GST and how it will help.

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:42.000
[Guest 2]: But, you know, the way the GST has been implemented instead of helping businesses, it's actually killed them.

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:51.000
[Guest 2]: Or he's talked about the fact that how the government is borrowing less, which is extremely stupid because all the government has done is it…

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:58.000
[Guest 2]: You know, the capital expenditure that the government used to carry out has now been simply moved off the books.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:02.000
[Guest 2]: So, you have Indian Railways borrowing through the Indian Railways Finance Corporation.

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:09.000
[Guest 2]: You have Food Corporation of India not being paid the amount that has to be paid.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:20.000
[Guest 2]: Or you have companies like ONGC being forced to buy HPCL and in the process, sort of bailing out, you know, borrowing to bail out the government.

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:25.000
[Guest 2]: And debt, which should have ended up on the books of the government has ended up on the books of ONGC.

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:34.000
[Guest 2]: So, I mean, you know, if you look at the things that are being done, I don't think, you know, I mean, one is the government does not do anything.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:36.000
[Unknown]: That's fine. I mean, if the government does not do, that's better.

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:42.000
[Guest 2]: But they're doing things and in the process, screwing up a lot of things.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:44.000
[Amit Varma]: So, I think I broadly agree with you.

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And what you're basically saying is, as Gurcharan Das said, India grows by night and as I said a little while ago, that whatever India does is because of Indian society in spite of the Indian state.

00:55:53.000 --> 00:56:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And what you would do is number one, acknowledge that there's a jobs problem and number two, put in whatever different small fixes you can, most of which will involve the government getting out of the way.

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Kumar, what's your take on this besides acknowledging the problem?

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:10.000
[Guest 1]: So, yeah, I think my answer to the questions would be the same.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:16.000
[Guest 1]: I think once you do the first, do the second, the problem of jobs gets taken care of in some ways.

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:25.000
[Guest 1]: And I, if you know, as a government, government should not be worried about creating jobs, you know, that's not the job of the government in any case.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:31.000
[Guest 1]: So, what you do is you focus on public goods, of course, don't worry too much about provision of private goods.

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:33.000
[Guest 1]: And you try to enable an environment where the jobs come in the private sector.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:41.000
[Guest 1]: And what I mean there is that you work, focus more on economic freedom, you know, not so much on ease of doing business.

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:53.000
[Guest 1]: So, what has happened, all the headlines in the last four or five years from the time the current government has come to power, you see a secular decline or increase, you know, betterment of the ranking of India on ease of doing business.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:57:07.000
[Guest 1]: And if you look into the disaggregation, the indicators which goes into, you know, building up the ease of doing business ranking itself, you realize those are things which could have been quick fixed using some notification by the government.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:10.000
[Guest 1]: And it takes care of, of course, Delhi and Mumbai. I mean, a lot has been written about it.

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Wherever there is a metric, it can be gamed.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:16.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so sort of. Those are things which are easy for the government to do.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:18.000
[Guest 2]: At least now it is being gamed.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:23.000
[Unknown]: But it is only being gamed. There is no actual…

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:27.000
[Guest 1]: What Vivek said in the beginning, you know, it's about all goes into building the narrative.

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:37.000
[Guest 1]: So, most recent, I think, if I remember correctly, I read a recent piece with a headline which said Narendra Modi now wants to have India's ranking under 50.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:40.000
[Guest 1]: Probably next time around, right now it's 77.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:49.000
[Guest 1]: While, interestingly, if you look at index of economic freedom, out of 186 about our country which gets ranked, India's ranking is 130.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:52.000
[Amit Varma]: And that is pretty much the same as it's been for the last…

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:53.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so that has not changed.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:58:06.000
[Guest 1]: So, a closer look at both the sub indicators of ease of doing business and economic, you know, index of economic freedom would tell you that all the sub indicators for economic freedom are much harder to do because those would require institutional reforms.

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:11.000
[Guest 1]: While, you know, a notification could help you get an improvement in the ranking for ease of doing business.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:20.000
[Guest 1]: So, all you need to do is just make sure the institutions are right and take enforcement of contracts, those kind of things, property rights, you know, rule of law is working.

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:29.000
[Guest 1]: While, you know, step out of the way and that takes care of both, you know, the problem as you said in poverty and jobs.

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And given the fact that there is no demand for good economics, given the fact that the political economy is so convoluted and all the parties seem to think in the same kind of statist way, are you guys then hopeful that we can actually move in a better direction or is it just, you know, sit back and let things unroll and hope that nothing disastrous like demon happens again but otherwise it's the same old, same old is going to go on like this?

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:55.000
[Guest 1]: I may have been a bit cynical few years ago.

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:57.000
[Guest 1]: I'm not as much anymore, I think.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:58.000
[Guest 2]: Why?

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:01.000
[Guest 2]: Because he's a corporate economist now.

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:04.000
[Guest 1]: No, I used to be a corporate economist.

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:05.000
[Guest 1]: I'm not anymore.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:13.000
[Guest 1]: The thing is, it has become very difficult to differentiate between the options in front of a voter today.

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:16.000
[Guest 1]: You know, they look almost all the same.

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:22.000
[Guest 1]: People used to say the BJP is Congress plus cow, but even the Congress is Congress plus cow now.

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:23.000
[Guest 1]: Exactly.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:24.000
[Guest 1]: So, BJP is equal to Congress.

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:33.000
[Guest 1]: So, as a voter, if I'm in the marketplace, you know, and walking up to a polling booth and I don't see much of a difference, I think there would be some entrepreneurs.

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:38.000
[Guest 1]: It's a great opportunity for someone to come with a different set of ideas and say, look, they're all the same.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:40.000
[Guest 1]: And it's so obvious that they're all the same.

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:41.000
[Guest 1]: So, make your case.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:43.000
[Guest 1]: You know, I mean, we don't have a liberal party in India today.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:47.000
[Guest 1]: So, then the party was the last time and they wrapped up in 1971, 72.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:55.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you're saying it's okay, the political marketplace is not giving the people what they need, but there is a gap in the marketplace and that's why you're hopeful.

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:59.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I'm hopeful because it's become starkly that they are all equal.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:01.000
[Guest 1]: So, it has become very difficult to distinguish.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:02.000
[Guest 1]: So, then what's the point?

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:15.000
[Guest 1]: You know, when it's not a single party, well, it's still a multi-party system, you know, so it will be, I think, if someone makes a strong enough case and presents the right evidence, probably there is some hope there.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:22.000
[Amit Varma]: I hope some young political entrepreneur or I hope some young person listening to this decides to become a political entrepreneur because of your inspiring words.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And frankly, you said you were hopeful, but you didn't sound very hopeful to me.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Vivek, what's your…

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:31.000
[Guest 2]: I just wanted to go back to the budget.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:39.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, again, I mean, which is, you know, at the beginning, I said Piyush Goyal did a fantastic job of marketing the government.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:46.000
[Guest 2]: So, if you sort of, you know, heard him carefully, he talked about how low the inflation was, okay.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:54.000
[Guest 2]: Now, what he didn't talk about was that inflation was low because food inflation is in negative territory.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:57.000
[Guest 2]: So, basically, food prices have been falling.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:02.000
[Guest 2]: The other thing he talked about was how bandwidth prices have fallen.

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:06.000
[Guest 2]: Now, bandwidth prices have, what has the government got to do with it?

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:11.000
[Guest 2]: Or he talked about the fact that how airline traffic has doubled.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:15.000
[Guest 2]: And he attributed it to the fact that government has opened so many airports.

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:18.000
[Amit Varma]: These are the achievements of society for which the state takes credit.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:24.000
[Guest 2]: No, I mean, so the government may have opened no airports, but ultimately, you know, more and more people are actually…

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:25.000
[Guest 2]: Exactly.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:28.000
[Guest 2]: Again, no, flying between the bigger cities where the airports are already there.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:36.000
[Guest 2]: It's just that the private entrepreneurs, you know, the indigos and the spies jets of the world have many more flights now than used to be the case.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:48.000
[Guest 2]: So, okay, so the point here is that, you know, basically, all Indian politicians now are trying to create a narrative, okay.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:57.000
[Guest 2]: I think the one lesson that politicians have learned from Narendra Modi is, I mean, whether it's the right one or the wrong one, we don't know,

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:04.000
[Guest 2]: is that, you know, irrespective of what you do at the ground level, whether you deliver or you don't deliver,

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:10.000
[Guest 2]: what is more important is to create and spread the right narrative.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:11.000
[Guest 2]: Okay.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:15.000
[Guest 2]: And I think this is, you know, this will play out.

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:21.000
[Guest 2]: It's already playing out and it will play out even more up until the next Lok Sabha elections.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:23.000
[Guest 2]: But that's an answer about the politics.

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:25.000
[Guest 2]: Which is what I'm coming to.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:30.000
[Guest 2]: So, basically, you know, this again, you know, I'll go back to Hindi cinema.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:36.000
[Guest 2]: There's this movie called Kameene and in that, the title song had a lovely line,

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:40.000
[Guest 2]: Maasoom sa kabootar, naacha toh moor nikla.

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:41.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, Gulzar wrote it.

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:46.000
[Guest 2]: So, I think Indian politicians are going exactly the opposite way.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:50.000
[Guest 2]: You know, Maasoom sa moor, naacha toh kabootar nikla.

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:57.000
[Guest 2]: And I think, I guess that the way, you know, things are going currently, I mean, I'm really not,

01:02:57.000 --> 01:03:03.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, Anand might be optimistic, but I'm really not very optimistic.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:09.000
[Guest 2]: You know, all these, I mean, see, the thing is this, I mean, ultimately, we may continue to grow at 6%.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:16.000
[Guest 2]: And that over a period of time will, that will also pull out a lot of people out of poverty.

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:23.000
[Guest 2]: But the entire talk about, you know, India growing at 8%, 9%, and, you know, the demographic dividend coming good,

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:30.000
[Guest 2]: and, you know, the growth story remaining strong, and all that is not going to play out.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:39.000
[Guest 2]: And, you know, if you understand the basic laws of compounding, you know, a great, if you grow at 8%, 9%,

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:47.000
[Guest 2]: and if you grow at 6%, it makes a huge amount of difference over a longish period of time.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, I think Nitin Pai of the Takshashila Institution once calculated that 1% of GDP growth in a year brings 2 million people out of poverty.

01:03:56.000 --> 01:04:00.000
[Guest 2]: So that becomes the opportunity cost of having a lower growth rate than you otherwise.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:02.000
[Guest 2]: And it's a humanitarian kind of…

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:10.000
[Guest 2]: So if you grow at 9% a year, your real income doubles in 8 years, if you grow at 6%, your real income doubles in 12 years.

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:14.000
[Guest 2]: So I'm not very, I'm not too optimistic.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:20.000
[Amit Varma]: So it's kind of time to wind up because we've just got five minutes left in this interview.

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, we can't take any of the reader questions.

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Sorry for that. We'll definitely take all of those and any more that you provide.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Next time, let's just end on a note of hope. All of us sitting and you know, to use your brilliant Bollywood analogy from Kamine,

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:39.000
[Amit Varma]: all of us are basically looking at a kabootar and saying to ourselves, ye dil mange more.

